entry.title: Use a more plausible RSA size in subtle-crypto-concurrent
entry.content:
The test currently uses 256-bit RSA. For reference, that is so small

that it isn't even in the RSA factoring challenges. 512-bit RSA was

already factored in 1999. Moreover, the test pairs 256-bit RSA with

SHA-256, but 256-bit RSA isn't even large enough to hold SHA-256 hashes.



BoringSSL is starting to raise the minimum accepted RSA key, starting

with a floor of 512-bit, which is incompatible with this test. Per the

comments, this test wasn't set because 256-bit RSA was important, but

because RSA keygen isn't very fast. While true, it's not so slow that we

can't just test sizes matching reality, so bump this up to 2048.



There are other WebCrypto WPTs that test 512-bit RSA. I've left them

alone for now, though when we go to a minimum of 768-bit (for

background, 768-bit RSA has also already been factored, as of 2009),

we'll need to fix those too.

entry.title: Only restore dialog focus if focus is in the dialog
entry.content:
Context: https://github.com/whatwg/html/issues/8904



This patch prevents the behavior where closing a dialog focuses the

previously focused element from before the dialog was opened only if

focus is in the dialog when the dialog closes.



Without this, focus can unexpectedly shift away from an element which is

not going away, like a text input that the user is currently typing into

for example.



This matches the behavior we recently implemented for popovers.

entry.title: Refactor Screen AI Service interfaces.
entry.content:
The following changes are done:

- A factory interface is added for Screen AI to return interfaces to

access main functionalities only after library load and

initialization.

- Separate initialization interfaces are added OCR and Main Content

Extraction to avoid creating extra pipelines if user needs only one

functionality.

- OCR and MainContentExtraction functions are now loaded from the

library regardless of the flags that enable these functionalities.

This is done to reduce the need to access flags from inside service

and avoid layering issues (as now an ASH feature also uses OCR).

Since these functionalities are controlled from outside the

service, it is safe to load the functions as we know they exist in

the library but not used. LayoutExtraction functions are still

behind flag as the feature is highly in prototype mode and the

functions are not necessarily available in the library.

entry.title: [DIPS] Add UMA Histogram to log actual deletion actions
entry.content:
This CL adds a new histogram (Privacy.DIPS.Deletion{DIPSCookieMode}) for

better visibility on what actions are actually taken on incidental

parties (DIPS-eligible sites for deletion).



The resultant metric will reflect the different conditions that might

prevent enforcing state deletion of these DIPS-eligible sites, while

also stating when actual deletion happened.



The CL also improves accuracy on

Privacy.DIPS.ClearedSitesCount{DIPSCookieMode}'s collection by making

sure we don't double count in case a deletion procedure is postponed

CachedFlags themselves).

overrides, which blocks its migration to //base.

JNI.



This also adds a test to ensure flags aren't declared and not cached,

which is a common pitfall.

entry.title: Optimize canvas layer stack depth.
entry.content:
Canvas layers sometimes have to be implemented using two nested

`cc::PaintCanvas` layers, depending on which global rendering states

are enabled. Until, there had to be a one-to-one correspondence

between states in the canvas state stack and layers in the

PaintCanvas. This means that we were pushing extra canvas state

copies to the state stack, even though they served no actual purpose other than maintaining that one-to-one relationship.



With this CL, layers requiring two PaintCanvas layers only require a

single canvas state push.

entry.title: Add UMA histogram for causes of irregular LCP image load timing
entry.content:
This CL adds a UMA histogram to count the causes of irregular LCP image

load timing. This is a follow up CL to the previous

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4476487 in

that specific potential causes are being counted. They are

1, image being loaded from memory cache.

2, image being preloaded by the early-hints mechanism.

3, image being loaded from memory cache and preloaded by the early-hints

mechanism.

If none of the above is true when the load timing is incorrect, we

count the cause as unknown.



The information whether an image being loaded from memory cache and/or

preloaded by the early-hints mechanism are propagated from the

ResourceFetcher::RequestResource and passed from renderer to browser.



The UMA recording happens in the PageLoadTracker::OnTimingChanged()

method when a new LCP candidate is about to be updated.

entry.title: Add remoting-crash-uploader binary and friends
entry.content:
This CL adds a few classes and a binary which will be used to upload

CRD crash reports generated on linux. I've put the impls into a

crash-specific sub-directory as I'd like to reuse the impl for Mac as

well.



A brief overview of the crash lifecycle as it is implemented:



1) CRD binary crashes, an in-proc breakpad instance writes a dmp file:

/tmp/chromoting/.dmp

2) Breakpad calls our post-dmp handler which writes a metadata file:

/tmp/chromoting/.json



3) CrashFileWatcher instance sees the new metadata file and verifies

the dump file also exists

4) CrashFileWatcher instance moves the dmp and json file into:

/tmp/chromoting/

5) CrashFileWatcher signals CrashFileUploader that there is a dmp file

ready to be processed

6) CrashFileUploader reads the dmp and metadata contents and does some

validation on tham

7) CrashFileUploader generates a POST request and sends it to the Crash

collector service

8) CrashFileUploader deletes the dmp file and writes an upload_result

file with the result of the action



For #8, I want to leave the dir and metadata file around

for troubleshooting. For instance if someone says they experienced a

crash on their host, we can ask for the specific report_id which is

stored in the upload_result file.



Once this lands, I will follow up with a CL which incorporates the new

crash-uploader binary into the daemon script.

entry.title: ADPF - boost frame in the middle if frame production takes too long
entry.content:
The idea is:

- Start a timer in OnBeginFrame (with the deadline = ADPF target duration * const multiplier)

- If the frame production is finished before the timer expires (i.e. if AttempDrawAndSwap is called), cancel the timer

- Otherwise, report a fake actual_duration > target_duration to ask ADPF for extra CPU resources, so that the frame has a higher chance of getting produced before the system deadline



Local manual scrolling tests show some scroll jank reduction, but:

- The data is noisy, so it's hard to quantify the improvement (or even to be sure that it's actually an improvement)

- This can cause power usage increase



I believe we need a field experiment to see the impact.
